It may or may not be possible for us to tell what purpose it serves in the divine scheme of saving men from their sins; but none deny that it is part of us ; every soul has a touch of it ; humanity as a whole dedi— cates certain of her sons to its exclusive service. This faculty, either of making or, in its lesser degree, of appreciating that which is made, is the stronger for being stimulated by religious emotions ; but it will not, for it cannot, lend itself to special pleading. The sceptre of power passes from it the moment it is so lent.
